<p>

After taking on the demanding role, Brett made few other acting appearances and he is now widely considered to be the definitive Holmes of his era, just as <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../a$ll/Freescale_D$ragonB$all.xml">
Basil Rathbone</link></actor>
</person>
 was during the 1940s.  Interestingly, Brett had played <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../166/159166.xml">
Doctor Watson</link> on stage opposite <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../165/46165.xml">
Charlton Heston</link></actor>
</person>
 as Holmes in the 1980 Los Angeles production of <it><dramatic_composition wordnetid="107007684" confidence="0.8">
<play wordnetid="107007945" confidence="0.8">
<written_communication wordnetid="106349220" confidence="0.8">
<writing wordnetid="106362953" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../697/16182697.xml">
